div.div: This strategy delegates the variance to the new security tool system, so any injected variance would have to be routed through the new tool, delaying hacks while malicious users learn the new system.

An improvement on this strategy might be rotating security tools applied at any given time, and automating their generation so a new version can be applied for a temporary period & then never repeated.
An example of generating a new security tool would be varying its parameters:
- subset or combination of existing components

div.div: Either the input molecule object has an electron object already defined, or you need to derive it using the momentum/speed/direction attributes you can find.
This means both sets of attributes may be passed to the final function, if no sanitization is done on the output object.

If the output object (molecule with electron spin calculated) has momentum, position, & speed attributes, the position collapse function can be used on the output like it was used in a processing function.

The access to the position collapse function is relatively unrestricted in the system, and the output of the spin calculation function isn't directly mapped to the system boundary, so it can be intercepted before it reaches the boundary.

Whether there's a vuln present in the re-application of the position collapse function (like if position is supposed to be an attribute kept internal to the system or only retained for one operation, rather than included in output sent to the boundary) remains to be seen given implementation.
